LEPTOSPIROSIS, HEPATITIS A - FIJI: (BA), CONTAMINATED WATER SOURCE
******************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

[1]
Date: Sat 16 Nov 2013
Source: The Fiji Times Online [edited]
http://www.fijitimes.com/story.aspx?id=251443


400 families in the interior of Ba have been affected by an outbreak of communicable diseases [hepatitis A and leptospirosis] that stemmed from a [contaminated] water source. Prime Minister Commodore Voreqe Bainimarama confirmed this during a visit to the affected water source yesterday [15 Nov 2013]. So far, 12 confirmed cases of hepatitis A and 23 cases of leptospirosis have been reported by health authorities.

Commodore Bainimarama led a government delegation consisting of WAF, district officers, medical and police officials. He was also briefed by a team of health officials who have been monitoring the area since the 1st suspected cases were reported earlier this week. Ba health officials revealed that the dam owned by Ba company MR Dayal and Sons was alleged to have been contaminated by nearby farmlands and animals that freely roam the unprotected water source.

Areas affected include Nukuloa, Tabataba, Moto, Nacaci, Balevuto, and Vatusui. Also located within these areas are 4 schools that also depend on the water source. Concerned for the residents that have now been without water since the Waica dam was shut down earlier this week by health officials, the Prime Minister ordered immediate action to be taken by authorities. He said the government could not afford to leave residents without water or with a contaminated water supply.

[Byline: Repeka Nasiko]

