Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The above articles say that Fiji authorities have implicated contamination of a community's water source to account for an outbreak of leptospirosis and hepatitis A in the community. The 1st article says that the water was contaminated from runoff of nearby farmlands and from animals that freely roam the unprotected water source. The articles, however, fail to say how this was established. Was fecal contamination of the water supply determined? Were hepatitis A virus and _Leptospira_ specifically identified at some point in the community's water supply?

Leptospirosis is transmitted to humans by exposure to soil or fresh water contaminated with the urine of wild and domestic animals (including dogs, cattle, swine, and especially rodents) that are chronically infected with pathogenic _Leptospira_. Humans, however, rarely become chronic carriers. _Leptospira_ may survive in contaminated fresh water or moist soil for weeks to months. Outbreaks of leptospirosis in Fiji frequently follow heavy rainfall, flooding with fresh water, and increasing rodent numbers.

Hepatitis A also is transmitted to previously uninfected (and unvaccinated) persons by ingestion of contaminated food or water, as well as by person-to-person contact, primarily by the fecal-oral route. In contrast to leptospirosis, only humans and non-human primates become infected with hepatitis A, and hepatitis A has no carrier state. From my brief search on the Internet, there are no non-human primates on Fiji, which suggests that if the water supply is the source, hepatitis A virus is being shed in feces from active cases of hepatitis A in the community, and that there is human sewerage contaminating the water source.

In addition to improved sanitation, ensuring a supply of safe drinking water, and food safety, immunization against hepatitis A has been used successfully to control community-wide outbreaks (http://www.who.int/mediacentre/factsheets/fs328/en/). The CDC recommends, after exposure to hepatitis A virus, a single dose of hepatitis A vaccine or serum immunoglobulin (IG) (0.02 mL/kg) be given as soon as possible, within 2 weeks after contact with the virus to unvaccinated persons aged 1-40 years (http://www.cdc.gov/hepatitis/hav/havfaq.htm). For persons aged 40 years and older and for children aged less than 12 months, IG is given, and IG should also be used in immunocompromised persons, persons with chronic liver disease, and persons who are allergic to the vaccine or a vaccine component. Hepatitis A vaccine should also be optimally included in the routine series of childhood immunizations.

Ba is a town in the province of the same name that occupies the northwestern sector of Viti Levu, Fiji's largest island. Fiji is an island nation in Melanesia in the South Pacific Ocean, about 2000 km (1300 miles) northeast of New Zealand's North Island (http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fiji). Fiji is divided into 4 major divisions: Central, Eastern, Northern, and Western. For a map of Fiji's divisions, see http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Fiji_divisions_named.png. The HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map of Fiji is available at: http://healthmap.org/r/0iMw. - Mod.ML]
